and so he he ran his his department somewhat he ran his department
different I tried to run mine by setting example and having people do try to do
what I was doing by example he ran his kind of like you'd run the army and he
had him jumping around pretty now the nickname for him was mom Samang yeah
well that was with the students yes they referred to him as mom Samang I'm not
sure I guess he took pretty good care of the students dr. Lindsay used to just
spend his time all time with students helping them with degree program and I
think that's a real important
thing to do and I think today they've got one of our problems is we've got
people helping students a degree program don't even know never took some of the
courses and really don't have we don't then that's one of the most important
features you're dealing with people's lives and this is where we ought to have
I had old dr. Harris and he had the patience of job helping those people
WD Harris in in chemical engineering he I put him in charge of that instead of
my doing it I put him in charge of because he had more patience than I did
you and dr. Lindsay came by one day and he says Charles I want to congratulate you
you finally put Don Harris to work I never could get him to work like that
and he came over there and old Don was in there just taking his time there's a
whole line of students out there waiting for him but he treated every one of them
and gave him his very best opinion and if you've got a kid in school you surely
appreciate somebody like that all right in those years in for an
undergraduate in chemical engineering what were the key courses key
undergraduate courses for those students oh they took unit operations and
thermodynamics much the same as taken now it really these fundamental things
really don't change all that much and we got we introduced process control after
in early fifties that was introduced by bleed GL fair then we in that group also
introduced chemical engineering ultras say program engineering and it kind of
Kinetics and Catalysis, one of the first schools in the country to do that.
And so ours got those, they had Unit Operations Laboratory and so on.
Unit Ops was one of them that they used a lot.
Dr. Lindsay taught a course in organic chemistry, and he kind of waited, he kind of threw the
grades and let, threw the papers and let the step they landed on determine the grade.
That's kind of, and some of them would really complain because he also looked and see which
student needed the grade, helped him determine it was.
According to the students, what were the toughest courses for them to pass?
Which ones?
Well, I imagine one of the first ones in those years was the very first one, the Industrial
Stoichiometry course, and after that probably the Thermal course.
And I've taught, I've taught every, see all the time I was department head, I taught one
or two courses, and I've taught all the graduate courses over there, and I've taught all the
undergraduate.
I believe every last one of them, they've added one or two now that I haven't taught,
but basically I had to teach a lot when we didn't, because we had, there were three of
us there, Dr. Harris, Dr. Lindsay, and me, two full professors and assistants.
Well, who had the heavy load?
I was teaching about all, everything, but it didn't, it stood me in good stead later
because I was, I had information and knowledge in all those fields when I'd go doing research.
I could pull on thermometers.
I could pull on a thermo or any of the others.
You mentioned Smang as one of your key associates as a department head.
Who were some of the others?
Well, Al Cronk was one.
Chris Browneman was first head of technology over there.
Charlie Crawford, I think he was, he won the, he was head when I became head.
Bob Whiting was head.
And I believe Mr. Langford sat in.
Yeah.
He was on the, he may have still been head whenever I became head, but they had several
after that.
Let's see, then Jim Earl came along after Street.
Those were the main ones, but I knew the department heads over in agriculture.
Let me just tell you something.
I'm not, I know you probably figure that the faculty senate is the way to do it, because
a lot of them do.
But I have, I think that the prime minister approach that we had back in those years is
far superior.
Because all the faculty senates turned out to be as an advisory council to the president.
And what we had in those years was what was like the prime minister where the leader has
to come in and face the music.
And you've got all the people that have got authority there.
And then if there's a question, the faculty is the one that ends up settling it.
Because they'll appoint a committee.
But it was a chance to see whether you got.
Yeah.
And Rudder withstood that.
He handled that.
What I've found doesn't work about a faculty senate is that they don't take responsibility
for their recommendations.
They don't.
They recommend that somebody else do something and they walk away.
I know it.
And I've always wondered why couldn't we kind of combine the two where we would have an
advisory group, that's, I mean a group that's appointed.
Yeah.
And a group that's elected and they have to work it out together.
Well, I think having the department heads in there and the deans is really critical.
Because these are the people that really have to make it all work.
Those are the people that are really responsible for running the university.
And anything you do, you need to get all their approvals.
And the way it is, we don't have that joint meeting that they had then because we knew
what they were doing over in agriculture, their feelings on anything.
And I think that was a big mistake.
When we went from, to being, and let me just say, while I'm saying about that, and the
reason we went, I think, is because all the other universities are doing it.
We need to be like everybody else.
And that's what irritates me today, is to hear we want to be like so and so.
We want to be like them.
Well, you're never going to be number one.
Being like somebody, the best you can ever be is number two.
And what I believe is we are so unique and always have been that we ought to be ourselves.
Yeah.
And do the things that we think are best for us and our country, regardless of what these
rankings turn out.
Because those rankings they're turning out, you're beginning to see now, there's a lot
of criticism of them in the journals.
They don't mean much.
But everybody just throws them at one another, and they're always talking about how good
so and so is, how good so and so is.
And instead of talking about it, they ought to be out doing something.
All right.
Back in the early 60s, you and I served together on that Century 6.
Yeah.
Yeah.
Yeah. Yeah.
Yeah. Yeah.
Yeah. Yeah.
Yeah.
Yeah.
Yeah. Yeah.
And I remember there was one study where we were to make recommendations as to what
we thought A&M ought to aspire to be in 1976.
Summarize, as you recall, what that group did and how it operated.
Well, I think they had different task force that were making different studies.
And I was one under Gus Watkins, who was then Dean of Agriculture.
And I think Gus was the one thing I remember.
remember, because that was the hottest topic there was in those years, was the Corps Cadets.
And we thought the Corps was a good thing, but we didn't think it ought to be compulsory.
And we made that recommendation, and I think old Watson hated to go up with it, but we
did.
And I don't know, that overshadows the other thing that we looked at, and I don't
remember what all those were so much that, and I've forgotten, probably about that same
time we're concerned about having women here, and of course that would have been another
issue, and they would have been opening it up for women, too.
And we felt like that for
us to, if we did not do that, we were going to dwindle down to a little 2,000 student
a year military college.
Do you remember, in your working days,
working group, task force, sometimes we called it a working party, do you remember anybody
disagreeing with that recommendation?
There wasn't anybody in our committee that did.
I didn't remember either.
But old Gus was a little bit wavery sometimes, and I think actually he may have got sent
down on some of those South American trips because of him turning in what he turned in.
I don't know.
Do you remember what the argument was?
What the arguments were, other than that it wouldn't be, we wouldn't grow in enrollment.
You remember any other arguments?
Well, it just wouldn't be a first class university.
We'd just be a little military
school and then be, that's what it would be noted for, that we just would not have the
impact that we should have on the state of Texas if we got down to just simply a military
school.
In one of the early drafts that I wrote to summarize all of that, that it got to a point,
uh-huh.
That it got edited out, I think, I think I put in a phrase that we were afraid that
if we don't make these changes, we may end up very much like VMI or the Citadel.
Citadel, we had exactly the same thing.
That, uh, would end up, uh,
They didn't want to run them down, I guess.
Do you remember, do you remember anybody being afraid to speak for that?
There wasn't anybody in our committee.
Well, see, it was up to Gus.
Gus was the only one that might have had a problem.
We
were telling him what to say.
And so, you can get a little bit of a stronger position
about it if you don't have to make the statement yourself to them.
But I think that group would
have stood on what they felt.
There just wasn't that, I mean, it was a pretty evident thing
because you see, we had done everything Rutter had tried for, wanted us to do.
We went over
and canceled those corps, you know, to, you know, to, you know, to, you know, to, you
know, to try to help them and do all that thing and still it didn't grow.
It just went
up very gradually and we just weren't making it.
And so, we did everything that he could
think of that, that, uh, to try to, try to make it go the way it was and it just wouldn't
do it.
As you recall, when the, uh, board, then it was called Board of Directors, now Board of
Regents.
When they approved the changes, do you remember how you and other faculty members
reacted?
What was your impression?
No, I really don't.
Uh, I, I guess I just felt like it was, it, it had to come.
Uh,
I guess the thing that really surprised me, well, it didn't surprise me at all, but my
conclusion was it would take somebody like Rutter, who, uh, the former students could
look at and say if, if that man, as strong as he was for the corps and all the things
he did, if he thinks it ought to go that way, then we're going to have to go along with
his decision, I think.
I think that's what it took to get somebody with his credibility to do it.
And I'll tell
you, I've been over there two different summers, uh, where Pointe du Hoc and looked at, been
in that, uh, in that dugout there and they've got inscribed and the, the guide the last
time I was there, she had more to say.
In fact, there's more said about him and all
the guides and everything, anybody else.
It's not Eisenhower and them, it's him.
And they
have a big discussion about him on all the tour guides going in there.
Let me add, for the sake of this tape, when I first met General Omar Bradley, was, uh,
at the Sun Bowl game about January 1, 1981 in El Paso.
I had just gone out there.
He
was old physically, meaning he was in a wheelchair, couldn't walk, but his brain was still young.
He looked up at me and said, you're from Texas A&M.
Yes, sir.
Uh-huh.
Did you know Earl Rudder?
Yes, sir.
I worked with him.
His voice broke a little and he
said, in all of my 48 years of command responsibility, I never gave a tougher order to any officer
than the one I gave to Earl in his outfit the night before D-Day because if they hadn't
got, made it successfully up Pointe du Hoc and knocked out the German artillery, we would
have had a massacre on both Omaha and Utah.
Well, I didn't understand what he meant until I saw Pointe du Hoc two or three years later
and realized, yes.
Uh-huh.
Well, you know that, uh, I've, I've heard that same thing from, uh, that he'd
said it before.
Uh, it's in some print or some, uh, news somewhere, uh, that this was
the toughest assignment that anybody had during World War II.
And, uh, so he was really revered
over there.
They left that thing just the way it was.
How much did you and your colleagues in engineering, how often, how much did you all see of Mr.
Rudder while he was president?
I saw him a lot more.
Not, he didn't run over there much.
But, see, when people would give
us money, uh, I would, uh, he would, we would always go to his office.
And so he got to
see everybody.
And I got rel, well acquainted.
We'd sit down and shoot the breeze a while
and then we'd go eat lunch together.
Uh-huh.
In fact, I had lunch with him over there.
I had lunch with him over in, uh, over in that, uh, Sabisa Hall, that dining room.
Just
a few days, he'd already had a stroke.
And I could tell his lip was kind of, wasn't moving
much.
And I thought there was something wrong with him.
But I got to know him real well.
And, uh, old Fred said, told me one time, he says, you know, I had a hell of a job selling
you to Rudder.
But I was just talking to him the other day and he said, boy, he's sure
high on you now.
Ha, ha, ha.
Ha, ha.
Ha, ha.
Ha, ha.
But, uh, no, I got to know him real well and, uh, because we met so many different times.
And he liked, he is different than some of the presidents.
He wanted to know what was
going on on the outside world.
What the businesses people were doing, what they were thinking.
That was one of the reasons he liked to eat with these, these people that were giving
us money.
He wanted to, to get their viewpoints on things.
And I, I think that he was not true.
I think he was a man of the house.
But you were not turned on by eggheads.
Oh, he wasn't.
He wasn't.
He told Fred one, and Fred told me this.
It was, they were, I remember there at one time, I had a hard time there running that
department.
I had so much help from Charlie Squires and old Andy Sutton, all those guys knew so much
more than anybody else.
And, and old Squires knew so much about everything that he couldn't run physics but one year.
Ha!
But, anyway.
Um, Fred told me this.
No, he was in, he was in naphtha.
told me this, that they ran out of a department head over there in physics.
And Mr. Rutter,
you know what his background was.
He had all these people over there who were big theorists
and so forth, and he called them in there in his office over in that old administration
building, and he said, we need to pick up a department head from among you people.
Which
one of you would make a good department head?
And he said, I've never heard people run one
another down so much in all my life.
And he said, they concluded there wasn't any of them
fit to be department heads.
But here he was.
He outmaneuvered that bunch of so-called eggheads
just so far ahead of them in his way.
That's the way it ended up.
But they,
they couldn't, they couldn't handle the situation.
He handled it.
All right, you mentioned two men, Squire and Suttle.
Go back and describe for this recording
Dr. Suttle.
Who was he and what was his task?
Well, he came from Mississippi, and he worked under Liddy for his PhD.
And he also worked down
at Exxon.
At their research lab.
And I was talking with some of the Exxon people in research, and
they said he was the only guy down there never written a report all the time he was there.
And then I had one year, to give you a really feel about it, I had Jim Galloway, who's one
of our former students, about the class of 20-something, and he was head of all production
for Humboldt Oil and Refining Company.
And Charlie Jones, whom I'd met the summer I worked
down there and got acquainted with.
I had him come up and speak to the engineering faculty.
And so as we were going from the airport
over to the, I was going to take him over and let him visit Rutter.
And as we were going
from the airport, they said, well, we'll run by and see Andy just run through his office.
They said, by the way, what do you think of him?
I said, well, you know, he's probably done some good and some bad.
I hear he came to us highly recommended from Exxon.
See, they want to get rid of you.
Old Charlie said, well, he is a great scientist.
And then old Jim Galloway said, yeah, he's a great scientist.
And so he said, well, we'll just, he said, Charlie says, you know, he is an odd duck, isn't he?
So they said, well, we'll just kind of run through his office and then go on in and talk to Rudder.
Now, his task was, he was vice president for research.
I really don't know what his job was.
He had an office over there, kind of an advisor.
And Fred Smith told me another funny one on him.
You knew Fred Smith that taught geology?
Well, he had advised students every once in a while.
And according to Fred, they had some of these science students up here.
And one of them wanted to talk to a real authority about nuclear energy.
And so who else would be better than somebody that worked under Liddy?
So they lined him up over there.
But when she called him up, the girl did, he made an appointment at night over in his office.
And it just had this lady running the dorms just all upset about it.
And when she went to Rudder with it, that he'd had that girl over there at night.
And Rudder went, they said, went storming down the hall.
And he said, well, he's a real man.
And she said, well, he's a real man.
And he said, well, he's a real man.
That's the second damn mistake he's made this week.
But I always had a lot of help with how I ought to be running the department from both
Squires and Andy Suttle.
Right now, did Squires succeed Andy as vice president?
No, actually they were both here at the same time, and Squires was kind of working over
in the science and Andy was kind of over in the system.
They got along very well together, but they were always telling everybody else how to
run their business.
They were going to help Rutter improve A&M College, Texas A&M University.
All right, let's see, let's go back to Wayne Hull as vice president for research.
I guess when you
became, I mean vice president for academic affairs, when you became a department head.
Well he had it.
He had been a department head in science, I mean in plant science, and then he moved
up to become, and he held that for a long time.
And then he succeeded by
Coonsey.
No, yeah, Coonsey was a graduate dean.
A graduate dean, well that's what Hull was for a long time.
Hull was a graduate dean.
He was both.
He was both.
He was both.
Vice president for academic and graduate dean.
Oh, okay.
Well I used to meet with him.
I used to serve on those committees.
In fact, one of the first committees I served on was with, I used to serve on the curriculum
committee when I served with Heaton, Al Chalk, and Mr. Godby, if you remember back that far.
We were on, and old Ty Timm was turning courses into us every time you flipped a switch, he
had a course in.
Ty Timm.
Ty Timm did.
Yeah.
Who did, in those days, campus wide, who do you think were the most influential people
other than, than Mr.
Rudder?
Whose opinion did Mr.
Rudder listen to?
Oh, I think he took, I think he took Benson's opinion over most all the others.
Okay.
And I don't know he asked it, I don't know whether he took it, because Benson told me
that if somebody from outside criticized me, jump, jump, jump.
Jump through his asshole.
We better take that off.
But he said that, you know, if they said anything, he didn't, he didn't always accept it, but
he accepted stuff on the outside more.
But I think he was, I think Benson was the one he always turned to on about all the problems.
Now, those, I as a junior faculty member in history, I and my buddies heard that of the
four deans, the only two that really had a vote that mattered was the Dean of Engineering
and the Dean of Agriculture.
Uh-huh.
I imagine that.
That Arts and Sciences didn't matter much and Vet Medicine was so small.
Yeah.
And that Benson, serving through a long time as Dean of Engineering, that he mattered
most.
Uh-huh.
Now, you served as department head for how long?
Twenty-three years, from 64 to 87.
Wouldn't you be, wouldn't, you were the senior department head?
Yeah.
By far, weren't you?
Yeah.
Um.
Actually, the only, the biggest reason they wanted to get rid of him is because he had
served 23 years.
And I mean, they were really on me to, uh, you get to a point where regardless of what
you did, they're still going to be after you.
And I had told them I was going to retire in August of 87.
And they were having some awards meeting up there.
And I said, well, Charlie, why don't you just step down right now and we can start
hunting.
I mean, not right now, but step down here in a month or two and then we can start looking
for a new department head.
I said, well, I told you I was going to step down in August.
What's wrong with that?
Well, we could just do so much better if you'd just step down.
And I said, well, I did.
And I said, well, I don't care to until the time allocated.
And so they got Richardson in there and they went at it again.
I said, when Richard's, I said, if you want me to step down so damn bad, I'll quit this
minute.
Do you want it?
And that was the end of it.
He didn't want it that fast.
And so I had, uh, I served on until exactly when I told them I was ready to step down.
All right.
Let's, let's go back.
Mr.
Rudder.
Mr.
Rudder dies in early 1970 arranged for him to give a paper over in, uh, uh, I believe
it was Atlanta and I'd written it on continuing education.
And I went in to see him and he, he, I believe it was really dragging on him.
Cause he said, Charlie, I just don't see how I can do this.
I said, sure.
You can do it.
All you gotta do is read it.
I'll write the dang thing.
All you got to do it.
Read it.
And Morgan was, used to be here as president was the one that was, had asked me to give
him, uh, get some, get him to give a paper.
And, uh, so it turned out that Fred Benson had to read it.
He had the stroke before that occurred.
So I'd just been over his office a little before that.
All right.
Then we briefly had Clyde Freeman, I believe it is, as the interim and then Jack Williams.
Let's see.
No, uh, we had, uh, Ludeke.
Oh, I'm sorry.
General.
General Ludeke.
General Ludeke.
General Ludeke.
Yes.
Uh huh.
Yes.
Um, did Ludeke have any, did you have any interaction with him?
Oh yeah.
He asked me to look into this faculty club and I looked all over the place and found
out that unless you had drinks, if you wanted one to make profit, you're going to have to
have something like that.
And another thing that I asked him to do, and it was already too late.
I said that way, that thing is designed over there.
You can't have a meeting in it and it needs to be to where you can have all the people
in there.
So, uh, something in the faculty club that's a dinner of some sort where you have a speaker
and that way you can, it can make money that way.
And he said, well, it's too late to change it.
And he wanted me to, uh, and I did and I finally just reported to him that, that, uh, I didn't
think that they could not make a go of it, uh, unless they had some, and they, it's,
I've been proven correct.
I was, I was a junior member of that committee.
Uh-huh.
For that, all of that expansion of the MSC and the Rudder Tower.
And I was arguing the same thing as you because the faculty club on the 11th and 12th floors,
each of those little dining areas is so small that you can't get enough people in one place.
Uh-huh.
And so I told them that and it wasn't.
But the architect, uh, his.
They, somebody saw it, one in Dallas like that.
And I think I've eaten in that one in Dallas.
Uh-huh.
And that's the way they wanted it designed.
That's the reason it got designed that way.
Yeah.
And Rudder, and, uh, Ludeke said, well, it's just too late, you know, to change it.
And he accepted it.
He just didn't like it much, but he, I just told him, you know, we just can't, uh, it's
hard enough to get people to go out at night and eat anyway.
What would you, what, uh, description would you give of the manner in which he filled
in as the interim president?
Oh, I think he's, I think he was an excellent individual.
I think General Ludeke is one of the top.
One of the top people that, uh, and actually Fred told me that General Rudder got him, uh,
just hired him.
And Fred said, I tried to get him to take Ludeke and let him help him administer, and
he wouldn't do it.
He wanted to do it all himself.
And so he gave him to me, but, uh, he ran the station.
I worked for him some under there, but he was really, uh, uh, a nice individual.
Describe his, uh.
Very.
Low key, but very definite.
I sat with him on committee meetings and he didn't, uh, throw his former rank or anything
around.
And, uh, in fact, I was just over interviewing the, uh, transportation department.
His son is named Al Ludeke and he's a head of all planning over there.
And I didn't know about it until I called over there.
The same Al Ludeke.
Here?
He went to A&M, but his son, Al Ludeke's son is also named Al Ludeke and he's running the
planning division of the Texas, uh, Transportation Department, TxDOT.
And I went over and we had an interview with him and, uh, and, uh.
The few times I was in his office, I never saw a more orderly, cleaner desk.
Everything seemed to be in order, uh, and, uh, with me, he asked very few questions,
but they were always very specific.
He was very skillfully planned and he seemed to be an extremely good listener.
Mm-hmm.
Well, you see, what happened was that after the war, the, uh, Atomic Energy Commission,
they put him in, he was running that, but you never heard of him.
He doesn't, he wasn't out there making a lot of racket.
Mm-hmm.
Then they had trouble with that, uh, lab, that space laboratory out in, uh, Stanford.
And so they sent him out there and they, they'd been screwing up when he got out there.
It started to work.
Yeah.
And so everywhere he went, he was able to solve the problems and he didn't make a
big stir about it.
So I, I like.
He was a Chemical Engineering graduate, class of 1932.
Now, he came back after serving as Interim President.
He came back to Engineering.
Is that right?
Yeah, no, he was serving in Engineering before he ever became,
But, I mean, he went over to the President then?
Well, I'm not really sure he ever really served any over there.
I think that was just a discussion before.
And then whenever, when Rutter died, they took him out of engineering and made him acting president.
All right, but then after Williams came, he came back over to...
He may have, I don't really remember.
Jack Williams came.
Describe your impressions of Jack Williams as president.
Well, I think he was the man for that time.
I'm not really sure that I'd, I don't know that I'd rank him anywhere near Rutter.
I think Rutter's one of the best ones in here, that's ever been here,
but yet I would have given him the poorest chances when he came of anybody we've ever had.
But I think Jack did a good job as president,
and because of his academic background, he could see what was needed.
I think anything that he did...
I think anything that he did...
